I guess we should start this post at the beginning. Sorry I thought I did before, but I was a bit in a daze when I ended my last post on Bissau. I left off at the point where I boarded a plane to Banjul and a few hours later arrived home happy and exhausted. The trip was very full of ups and downs, beginning and ends, and more than had been planned for. Sometimes, that just goes with the territory.

The first few minutes after taking off was the hardest part of the trip for me in the (only slightly) puffy vest, scarf and fleece I had brought with me (for walking between the house, Assembleia, taxi area) with neither jacket or piling on at the embassy: it was 92 F. but I was already sweaty & sliding into that slightly hard seat while being quite overwhelmed by the language – there was no translation for “obrigada(“ to me yet (even if I had known the language a bit). I began to feel really lucky once we got started with reading about life in Africa, even with the connexion breaking off at times (it was better in Banjul than Conakry, and those aren’t broken lines of writing I want to strive for). But then I couldn’t find my emergency exit seat (or that row for that matter) after change ended up changing
